1. Introduction & Problem Statement
In the modern academic environment, students spend upwards of 8–10 hours in front of digital screens. This leads to two significant issues:
1.	Postural Kyphosis (Slouching): Long-term spinal misalignment due to poor sitting habits.
2.	Cognitive Fatigue: Decreased alertness and drowsiness during late-night study sessions, which reduces learning efficiency.
ErgoVision-AI is a Computer Vision-based solution designed to act as a "digital posture coach." It monitors the user in real-time via a standard webcam, providing immediate feedback on posture and detecting signs of drowsiness.
________________________________________
2. Proposed Solution
The project utilizes Human Pose Estimation and Facial Landmark Detection to quantify physical behavior.
Key Features:
•	Posture Analysis: Measures the angular relationship between the ear, shoulder, and hip to identify slouching.
•	Fatigue Detection: Implements the Eye Aspect Ratio (EAR) algorithm to detect prolonged eye closure (drowsiness).
•	Real-time Processing: Optimized for high-frame-rate inference on standard CPU hardware.
________________________________________
3. Technical Approach & Decisions
3.1 Tools & Libraries
•	OpenCV: Used for video stream acquisition, frame manipulation, and rendering the User Interface (UI).
•	MediaPipe (BlazePose & FaceMesh): Chosen over traditional CNNs because MediaPipe provides sub-millisecond inference on mobile and desktop CPUs, ensuring the "Real-Time" requirement of the project.
•	NumPy: Utilized for vector mathematics and coordinate geometry.
3.2 Posture Detection Logic
The system identifies three key landmarks: Left Ear ($P_1$), Left Shoulder ($P_2$), and Left Hip ($P_3$). Using the coordinates $(x, y)$, we calculate the interior angle $\theta$:
$$\theta = \arccos \left( \frac{\vec{P_{2}P_{1}} \cdot \vec{P_{2}P_{3}}}{|\vec{P_{2}P_{1}}| |\vec{P_{2}P_{3}}|} \right)$$
A threshold of 160° was established. Any angle significantly lower indicates the head is leaning forward (slouching).
3.3 Drowsiness Detection (EAR)
Instead of simple "eye-opening" detection, the system calculates the Eye Aspect Ratio.
The formula used is:
$$EAR = \frac{||p_2 - p_6|| + ||p_3 - p_5||}{2||p_1 - p_4||}$$
Where $p_1 \dots p_6$ are 2D facial landmark locations. When the ratio drops below 0.22 for more than 15 consecutive frames, a "Drowsiness Alert" is triggered.
________________________________________
4. Key Decisions & Challenges
•	Handling Variable Lighting: Initial testing showed that shadows on the face caused the Eye Mesh to flicker. I resolved this by increasing the min_detection_confidence to 0.7 and using a temporal frame counter to avoid "false positive" alerts from natural blinking.
•	Hardware Constraints: To ensure stability on devices that might experience camera lag (like high-resolution mobile sensors acting as webcaps), I implemented coordinate-based tracking rather than full-image classification to minimize memory overhead.
